/******************************************************** JAVA *********************************************/

Optimal Solution - We use a sliding window with a set to maintain unique characters, expanding the window with the right pointer and 
                    shrinking it from the left whenever a duplicate appears to track the longest valid substring.



class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        // Set to store unique characters in the current window
        Set<Character> charSet = new HashSet<>();
        // Stores the maximum length found
        int maxLen = 0;
        // Left pointer of the sliding window
        int left = 0;
        // Right pointer expands the sliding window
        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
            // If character already exists, shrink the window from the left
            while (charSet.contains(s.charAt(right))) {
                charSet.remove(s.charAt(left));
                left++;
            }
            // Add current character to the window
            charSet.add(s.charAt(right));
            // Update the maximum window size
            maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, right - left + 1);
        }
        // Return the length of the longest valid substring
        return maxLen;
    }
}

Time Complexity :- O(n).
Space Complexity :- O(n).
